Harvard students take a course on how to rest enough
A new course at Harvard University this year has driven all its students to sleep more in the attempt to counter the growing manly culture of studying for whole nights fed by caffeine.
A university student found that students at the university number one in the world often have no idea of the basic concepts of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he considers to be the first of this type in the USA.
He had the idea of starting the course after a conference that had given about the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
"At the end a girl came to me and said to me, 'Why did you just tell me this now, when I'm last year?'
He said that no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which made me very surprised," he told The Telegraph.
The course, given for the first time this year, explains to the students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits can help academic and athletic performance and improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of health services at the university, said that the university decided to introduce the course after finding out that students were suffering from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The course of an hour involves a series of interactive activities.
In a section there is the image of a bedroom, where students can select cups of coffee, curtains, gym shoes and books so they can know the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by lack of sleep, and the importance of a night routine.
In another section, participants are explained how the lack of long-term sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, therefore encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, just as you have the right to know the effects on the health of smoking choice," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride linked to the "white night studying", still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to a lack of sleep being a growing problem.
Sleeping enough and with a good quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, spousalness, anxiety, has explained and even should help avoid fattening because lack of sleep brings the brain into an inedy mode, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student enrolled in the Faculty of Chemical and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after having followed one of his lessons last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, hopefully, will be to ask all graduates to follow a similar study program before joining this competitive institute.
Prof Czeisler advised students to set up a wake for when they have to go to bed, as well as when they have to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted from electronic screens and LED lights, which can cause the circadian rhythm to tilt, leading to sleeping problems.
