Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup that tries to rival with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the legend of technology, Inrupt, is a company that brings its origins from Berners-Lee's open source Solid platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and what people will have access to and what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is to "dominate the world".
"We have to do it now," said the startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their "online personal data store" or a POD.
It can include lists of contacts, things to do, calendars, musical libraries and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available on one browser and at the same time.
The uniqueness of the store of personal data online is that it is completely at the user's option who can have access to what kind of information.
The company calls it "personal storage through data."
The idea for Inrupt, according to John Bruce, CEO of the company, is to provide adequate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some developers in the staff hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
From this week onwards, technology programmers around the world will be able to deliver their decentralised apps using the tools available on the Inrupt site.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team won't tell "Facebook and Google whether or not to introduce a complete change where their business models are completely unburdened from one day to the next.
"We're not asking for their permission."
In a post on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built from Solid".
In 1994 Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months Berners-Lee has represented an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Even after the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the Founder and Manager of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm incredibly optimistic about this new era of the web," said Berners-Lee.
