The new German military ship was postponed again
According to local media, the last frigate of the German military Navy would have to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the old military ships of the times of the cold war, but there will not be at least until next year due to defective systems and a cost impenedate.
The commission of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the admiral ship of the new frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class, was postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit citing a military spokesperson.
The ship was supposed to join the military Navy in 2014, but worrying questions after delivery tormented the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg ships ordered by the military Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen ships.
They will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some hidden technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic markings.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, in fact it should be possible to use new frigates up to two years away from national ports.
However, the continued delays imply that the innovative warships, which are said to allow Germany to project its power overseas, will become obsolete when they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The unfortunate F-125 frigate reported last year, when the German military Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the military Navy returned a ship to the manufacturer after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but the German media noticed a number of "defet software and hardware" crucial that made the ship useless if used in a combat mission.
The deficiencies in the software were particularly important because the Baden-Württemberg class ships will be managed by a crew of about 120 sailors, just half of the personnel of the oldest vessels of the Bremen class.
Moreover, it has emerged that the ship weighs definitely too much, and this reduces its performance and limits the possibility of the military Navy to add future updates.
Rheinland-Pfalz, of 7,000 tonnes, is believed to be twice as heavy as the ships of similar classes used by the Germans in the Second World War.
Apart from the defective hardware, the cost of the entire project (including crew training) is becoming an important issue.
It seems that it has reached 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion dollars) from the initial 2.2 billion euros.
The problems involving the new frigates are of particular importance in the light of recent alarms concerning the reduction of German naval power.
At the beginning of the year, Hans-Peter Bartels, Parliamentary Commissioner for the Armed Forces, admitted that the military Navy actually "loads ships capable of being used".
