Donald Trump, President of the United States, has already launched the first warning this year by taxing the main Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with the new duties on articles for over $200 billion (EUR 175 billion) of value. This means that taxes will be applied on half of Chinese goods.
Beijing has reacted every time with similar measures applying duties from five to ten percent of 60 billion US dollars of goods.
China has promised to respond to the US coup and it is unlikely that the second largest economic power in the world will soon march back.
Because Washington quits, it would have to yield to his demands, but publicly bending to the USA would be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, the President of China.
Experts however believe that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressures of trade war with the USA can affect China in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a rapid political decision by Washington or Beijing can create the initial conditions of an economic collapse in both countries is in fact much more dangerous than has been recognized so far," says Abigail Grace, a researcher who studies Asia at the research centre Center for New American Security.
Syria is "ready" for the return of refugees, supports the foreign minister
Syria claims to be ready for the return of refugees and is seeking help to rebuild the country devastated by over seven years of war.
In front of the United Nations General Assembly, the Minister for Foreign Affairs Walid al-Moualem said that the conditions of the country are improving.
"Today the situation on the territory is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to recover the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
Now there are all the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that have had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that have affected their daily lives and their livelihood.
According to the United Nations estimate, more than 5.5 million Syrians have abandoned the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Six million others still living in Syria need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem stated that the Syrian regime will gladly accept assistance to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that he would not accept any conditional aid from those countries that supported the insurrection.
