Update on the red tide: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentration in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, chiasse flowering conditions, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in areas of the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier.
The red tide bloom extends for about 130 miles of coast from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The talk is about 10 miles away from Hillsborough County but in less areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week an average concentration was reported in Pinellas County or off its coast, a concentration from low to high off Hillsborough County, from a concentration of bottom to high concentration in Manatee County, from a concentration of bottom to high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coast, from a concentration of bottom to middle concentration in Charlotte County, from a concentration of bottom to high concentration in Lee County or off its coast and a low concentration in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation cases continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
While no cases were reported in northwest Florida last week.
